amarantin command reference
===========================

Overview
--------
Repository operating notes for agents and contributors.

Purpose
-------
This repo is a small C++17 / ROOT project for building persistent ROOT-based
sample containers and derived dataset / event-list artifacts.

Primary code paths
------------------
io/              Core I/O library
ana/             Analysis-side helpers and event-list construction
syst/            Systematics cache construction
plot/            Plotting library
app/             Command-line tools
tools/           Helper scripts
samples-dag.mk   Higher-level sample workflow
datasets.mk      Sample-list declarations consumed by samples-dag.mk

Primary executables
-------------------
  * build/bin/mk_sample
  * build/bin/mk_dataset
  * build/bin/mk_eventlist

Canonical build path
--------------------
Treat CMake as the source of truth. Prefer out-of-source builds.

  cmake -S . -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release
  cmake --build build --parallel

Environment setup
-----------------
GPVM / Fermilab container
  source ./.container.sh
  source ./.setup.sh

Docker
  docker build -t amarantin-dev .
  docker run --rm -it -v "$PWD":/work -w /work amarantin-dev bash

Core build commands
-------------------
Configure
  cmake -S . -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release

Build everything
  cmake --build build --parallel

Build selected targets
  cmake --build build --target IO
  cmake --build build --target Ana
  cmake --build build --target Syst
  cmake --build build --target Plot
  cmake --build build --target mk_sample
  cmake --build build --target mk_dataset
  cmake --build build --target mk_eventlist

Sample workflow
---------------
Generate all sample lists from `datasets.mk`
  make -f samples-dag.mk samples-lists

Build all sample ROOT files from `datasets.mk`
  make -f samples-dag.mk samples

Print all managed sample outputs
  make -f samples-dag.mk print-samples

Remove generated sample ROOT files and sample lists
  make -f samples-dag.mk samples-clean

Generate one sample list directly
  tools/mklist.sh --dir /path/to/input --pat "nu_selection.root,nu_selection_data.root" --out samplelists/example.list

Build one sample ROOT file directly
  build/bin/mk_sample output.root input.list data nominal numi fhc

Dataset workflow
----------------
Build one persistent DatasetIO file directly
  build/bin/mk_dataset output.dataset.root context sample-key=sample.root

Build a DatasetIO file and stamp sample definitions
  build/bin/mk_dataset --defs sample.defs output.dataset.root run1-numi-fhc beam-s0=build/samples/run1/beam-s0.root

The plain text `sample.defs` format is:
  key variation nominal tag role defname [campaign]

Use `-` for an empty field.

Event-list workflow
-------------------
Build one persistent EventListIO file directly
  build/bin/mk_eventlist output.eventlist.root input.dataset.root

Build one persistent EventListIO file with explicit tree names and selection
  build/bin/mk_eventlist output.eventlist.root input.dataset.root EventSelectionFilter SubRun "selected != 0"

Build an EventListIO file and immediately cache one systematic payload
  build/bin/mk_eventlist \
    --cache-systematics beam-s0 topological_score 50 0 1 \
    --cache-selection "__pass_muon__" \
    --cache-detvars beam-s0-sce,beam-s0-wiremodx \
    --cache-fine-nbins 400 \
    --cache-genie \
    output.eventlist.root input.dataset.root

Macro runner
------------
Run one ROOT macro through the common wrapper
  bash tools/run-macro plot_event_display build/eventlists/run1.root beam-s0 0 U detector

Run a plotting macro directly through ROOT
  root -l -b -q plot/macro/cache_systematics.C

Notes
-----
`mk_sample`
  Accepts an optional `--run-db PATH`. If omitted, it checks
  `AMARANTIN_RUN_DB` and otherwise falls back to:
    /exp/uboone/data/uboonebeam/beamdb/run.db

`samples-dag.mk`
  Uses `build/bin/mk_sample` as its canonical producer and records small stamp
  files to avoid rebuilding unchanged sample outputs.

`mk_dataset --defs`
  Is the preferred place to stamp workflow metadata like `nominal`, `tag`,
  `role`, `defname`, and `campaign`.
